        <section
        id="fs-id1828656"
      >
            <title
        >Ohm&#x2019;s Law</title
      >
        <para
          xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0"
          id="import-auto-id1170614047620"
        >The current that flows through most substances is directly proportional to the voltage <m:math
          ><m:semantics
            ><m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
                ><m:mi
                  >V</m:mi
                ></m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
              /></m:mrow
            ><m:annotation
                encoding="StarMath 5.0"
              > size 12{V} {}</m:annotation
            ></m:semantics
          ></m:math
        > applied to it. The German physicist Georg Simon Ohm (1787&#x2013;1854) was the first to demonstrate experimentally that the current in a metal wire is <emphasis
            effect="italics"
          >directly proportional to the voltage applied</emphasis
        >:</para
      ><equation
          id="eip-103"
        ><m:math
          ><m:semantics
            ><m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
                ><m:mrow
                  ><m:mi
                    >I</m:mi
                  ><m:mo
                      stretchy="false"
                    >&#x221D;</m:mo
                  ><m:mi
                    >V</m:mi
                  ></m:mrow
                ></m:mrow
              ><m:mtext
                >.</m:mtext
              ><m:mrow
              /></m:mrow
            ><m:annotation
                encoding="StarMath 5.0"
              > size 12{I  prop  V.} {}</m:annotation
            ></m:semantics
          ></m:math
        ></equation
      ><para
          id="import-auto-id1170614065536"
        >This important relationship is known as <term
            id="import-auto-id1170614061213"
          >Ohm&#x2019;s law</term
        >. It can be viewed as a cause-and-effect relationship, with voltage the cause and current the effect. This is an empirical law like that for friction&#x2014;an experimentally observed phenomenon. Such a linear relationship doesn&#x2019;t always occur.</para
      >
        </section
    >
        
        <section
        id="fs-id3088760"
      >
            <title
        >Resistance and Simple Circuits</title
      >
        <para
          xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0"
          id="import-auto-id1170614065817"
        >If voltage drives current, what impedes it? The electric property that impedes current (crudely similar to friction and air resistance) is called <term
            id="import-auto-id1170614065376"
          >resistance</term
        > <m:math
          ><m:semantics
            ><m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
                ><m:mi
                  >R</m:mi
                ></m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
              /></m:mrow
            ><m:annotation
                encoding="StarMath 5.0"
              > size 12{R} {}</m:annotation
            ></m:semantics
          ></m:math
        >. Collisions of moving charges with atoms and molecules in a substance transfer energy to the substance and limit current. Resistance is defined as inversely proportional to current, or</para
      ><equation
          id="eip-593"
        ><m:math
          ><m:semantics
            ><m:mrow
              ><m:mrow
                ><m:mrow
                  ><m:mi
                    >I</m:mi
                  ><m:mo
                      stretchy="false"
                    >&#x221D;</m:mo
                  ><m:mfrac
                    ><m:mn
                      >1</m:mn
                    ><m:mi
                      >R</m:mi
                    ></m:mfrac
                  ></m:mrow
                ></m:mrow
              ><m:mtext
                >.</m:mtext
              ><m:mrow
              /></m:mrow
            ><m:annotation
                encoding="StarMath 5.0"
              > size 12{I  prop   {  {1}  over  {R} } "."} {}</m:annotation
            ></m:semantics
          ></m:math
        ></equation
      ><para
          id="import-auto-id1170614063309"
        >Thus, for example, current is cut in half if resistance doubles. Combining the relationships of current to voltage and current to resistance gives</para
      >
